article.description: The Atlanta Hawks can't afford to look past any team, even the lowly Denver Nuggets.
article.headline: Denver loses 14th straight on the road
article.linkText: Unlucky 13 hits Nuggets in loss to Hawks
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Hawks can't afford to look past any team, even the lowly Denver Nuggets. Shareef Abdur-Rahim hit a hook before Glenn Robinson made a clinching 3-pointer in the final minute as the Atlanta Hawks beat Denver 92-86 Tuesday night -- the 13th straight loss for the Nuggets. Abdur-Rahim finished with 30 points and 10 rebounds, and Robinson atoned for an atrocious shooting night to give the Hawks their second victory in six games. Robinson was 4-for-14, and missed all seven of his shots in the first half. At 23-38, Atlanta stayed 7½ games behind the eighth and final playoff spot. Denver fell to 12-49, only a half-game in front of Cleveland for the worst record in the league. "We're in the same situation as them," Abdur-Rahim said of the Nuggets. "We can't worry about who we're playing, we just have to go out and play." Denver has lost 14 in a row on the road, and has not won in Atlanta since 1988. Juwan Howard had 20 points for the Nuggets, and Nene Hilario added 14. "You go against a team like Denver, that doesn't necessarily have a good record, and you want to play well," Atlanta coach Terry Stotts said. "You'd like to have it be an easy game, but that's not always the case." Jason Terry had 17 points and 12 assists for the Hawks, finishing two rebounds short of his second-career triple double. He also had six turnovers. "Jason's something else," Stotts said. "His energy and activity, he keeps playing whatever happens. He just keeps on going." Vincent Yarbrough hit a wide-open jumper from the wing to put Denver ahead 86-85 with 1:09 left. But Abdur-Rahim responded quickly to give Atlanta the lead for good. He wheeled inside and his shot was blocked by Marcus Camby, but Abdur-Rahim recovered the ball and made a hook from just outside the paint. "I got the past the guy guarding me, but he got a piece of the shot," Abdur-Rahim said. "I stayed with it and saw I was in a pretty good situation, that I was open." With 30 seconds left, Howard shot an airball over Robinson, and Dion Glover grabbed the rebound. The Hawks patiently worked the shot clock down, and Glover found Robinson open in the corner. His 3-pointer swished through, giving Atlanta a 90-86 lead. "That was painful," Howard said of Robinson's shot. "I was praying it wouldn't go in. He hit a shot that was not supposed to go in." After Camby missed a layup, Theo Ratliff added two rebounds for the final margin. "We're right there," Howard said. "We just can't close it out at the end. I don't think we're jinxed, we're just learning. It's a hard time." Atlanta recovered from horrid shooting in the first quarter -- 7-for-24 -- to make 47 percent. "It's the same old story, we made careless passes throughout the game," Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik said. "That prevents us from building a lead or keeping a lead. It's that simple." The announced attendance was 9,392, but an unofficial count of fans came up with about 3,200. At least 10 suites were empty, along with four entire sections of the upper deck. Game notes
Before the game, the Hawks signed G-F Brandon Williams to a second 10-day contract. Williams hasn't scored in four games with Atlanta. ... The Nuggets have been starting four rookies: Hilario, Nikoloz Tskitishvili, Junior Harrington and Yarbrough. The last team to start four rookies was the Dallas Mavericks in 1992. ... Denver scored at least 80 points for a season-high sixth straight game.
